de.loki.metallum.entity.Review.name: Elder Has Freed Itself from Its Sabbathian Chains
de.loki.metallum.entity.Review.author: piexing
de.loki.metallum.entity.Review.text:
Elder's self-titled debut established its psychedelic brand of stoner doom metal, and the album's successor has refined and nearly perfected it. With Dead Roots Stirring, Elder has moved the focus from straightforward Sabbathian riffs to this style, and produced a more organic, more atmospheric and more mature album as a result.

The most notable elements of Dead Roots Stirring are those which differentiate it from its predecessor. The composition is freer; each riff flows into the next, with exception to the deliberate stops of the title track, and the riffs themselves are more nuanced overall, similar to the psychedelic breaks featured on Elder's self-titled. In accordance with this, the vocals are sparse and sung in a more natural style; the throaty chants Ã  la Dopesmoker are nowhere to be found.

Despite these differences, the best parts of Elder's first album remain: Some bits (much of "Knot" in particular) feature the more ordinary, though still unmistakably Elder, stoner doom style that dominated the band's debut, and every member again displays tight musicianship, an impressive feat considering the complexity of much of the composition. This complexity is what differentiates Elder from its primary influences; while the likes of Black Sabbath and Sleep are content to stick with a couple of simple, catchy riffs, Elder's music is more variable and expansive. Each song is nine to twelve minutes long not simply for the purpose of being long, but because that's the amount of time necessary for the song to naturally conclude. Dead Roots Stirring is its own beautiful beast, and "beautiful" truly describes the album.

Dead Roots Stirring shows that Elder has matured in its musical ability and carved its own niche into the already well-weathered stone of doom metal. Thanks to this, the band has crafted one of the finest doom releases in recent memory.
